# Part 1: Task Management

---

## When to Use

- New project with SPEC/requirements → break down into epics/stories/tasks
- Need progress tracking in files
- Working with AI agent on a project
- Tracking bugs

---

## CLI Tool: `task-board`

All board operations go through the `task-board` CLI. No manual file editing.

**Source repo:** your local `skill-project-management` checkout
**Installed skill artifact:** `~/.agents/skills/project-management` (degitized copy for agent runtimes)
**In PATH:** installed copy in `~/.local/bin/task-board`

Install/update the local binary before board setup:

```bash
cd /path/to/skill-project-management
./scripts/setup.sh
```

For a safe reinstall that refreshes binaries, the installed skill copy, roles, and install metadata without touching the current project's `task-board.config.json`, use:

```bash
./scripts/setup.sh --install-only
```

`--install-only` is now also the supported verification gate for rollout drift: it checks the installed `task-board` binary with `task-board q 'project_config()'`, requires the tracked background spawn contract fields to be present, and fails loud if PATH still resolves a stale `task-board` instead of `~/.local/bin/task-board`.

`task-board self-update` relies on `~/.config/task-board/install.json`, which is written by `scripts/setup.sh`. Do not treat `~/.agents/skills/project-management` as the update source; it is the installed artifact copy and has git metadata scrubbed.

`scripts/setup.sh` is the single supported install/update entrypoint for `task-board`, `task-board-tui`, and the installed skill artifact. `make install-*` targets are binary build helpers and do not replace setup.

When you bootstrap board-driven work inside a real code repository, prefer a single source-checkout setup command that also bootstraps the repo-local agent runtime through `alexis-agents-infra`:

```bash
cd /path/to/skill-project-management
./scripts/setup.sh --project-dir /path/to/project --mode local --board-dir .task-board --bootstrap-local-agents
```

`--bootstrap-local-agents` runs `agents-infra setup local /path/to/project` after writing the project config. Install the global `agents-infra` launcher once from the `alexis-agents-infra` source repo via `./setup.sh`, then use this shortcut for project repos.

That local setup makes project `.agents/` the installed runtime copy and refreshes `.claude/` + `.codex/` as thin shims into it. Do this right after board/config setup so spawned agents see the repo-local instructions, skills, and templates instead of drifting onto only global state.

### Quick Reference

All reads use `q` (query DSL), all writes use `m` (mutate DSL). Compact format (`--format compact`) saves tokens.

```bash
# Queries (reads)
task-board q 'schema()'                                                          # discover fields, presets, operations, mutations
task-board q 'project_config()'                                                  # effective project runtime config for this cwd; run before spawn or spawn-contract audits
task-board q --format compact 'summary()'                                        # board overview (counts + active/blocked)
task-board q --format compact 'get(TASK-260218-abc123) { full }'                 # full element details
task-board q --format compact 'list(type=task, status=development) { overview }'  # filtered list
task-board q --format compact 'list(type=task, blocked=true) { id name status }'  # blocked tasks
task-board q --format compact 'list(type=story, parent=EPIC-260218-abc123) { overview }'  # stories in epic
task-board q --format compact 'agents()'                                         # agent dashboard
task-board q --format compact 'plan(EPIC-260218-abc123, mode=children)'          # execution phases
task-board q --format compact 'count(type=task, status=done)'                    # count elements

# Mutations (writes)
task-board m 'create(type=epic, name=my-feature, description="...")'                        # create epic
task-board m 'create(type=story, parent=EPIC-260218-abc123, name=audio-capture)'            # create story
task-board m 'create(type=task, parent=STORY-260218-abc123, name=impl, description="...")'  # create task
task-board m 'set_details(TASK-260218-abc123, title="new title", description="...")'        # update README fields
task-board m 'rename(TASK-260218-abc123, name=better-task-name)'                            # update overview name/slug without changing ID
task-board m 'set_status(TASK-260218-abc123, status=development)'                           # change status
task-board m 'assign(TASK-260218-abc123, agent=claude-opus)'                                # assign agent
task-board m 'unassign(TASK-260218-abc123)'                                                 # remove assignment
task-board m 'link(TASK-260218-def456, blocked_by=TASK-260218-abc123)'                      # add dependency
task-board m 'unlink(TASK-260218-def456, blocked_by=TASK-260218-abc123)'                    # remove dependency
task-board m 'check_item(TASK-260218-abc123, item=1)'                                       # check checklist item
task-board m 'add_checklist_item(TASK-260218-abc123, text="Write tests")'                   # add checklist item
task-board m 'set_notes(TASK-260218-abc123, text="Progress update")'                        # append notes
task-board m 'set_notes(TASK-260218-abc123, text="Full replacement", set=true)'             # replace notes
task-board m 'set_parent(TASK-260218-abc123, parent=STORY-260218-def456)'                   # move to new parent
task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc123, name=TASK-260218-abc123_design.md, content="...", type=precondition, description="Architecture design")'  # create resource
task-board m 'update_resource(TASK-260218-abc123, name=TASK-260218-abc123_design.md, content="revised", type=precondition, description="Architecture design v2")'  # replace resource
task-board m --dry-run 'delete(TASK-260218-abc123)'                                         # preview destructive op
task-board m --confirm 'delete(TASK-260218-abc123)'                                         # execute destructive op

# Batching (semicolons)
task-board m 'assign(TASK-260218-abc123, agent=claude-opus); set_status(TASK-260218-abc123, status=development)'

# Spawn tracked background runs (--role and --background are REQUIRED)
task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc123 --role developer --background                    # queue tracked background developer run
task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc123 --role researcher --background                   # queue tracked background researcher run
task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc123 --role reviewer --background                     # queue tracked background review run
task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc123 --role developer --background --instruction impl-guide.md     # validate resource is linked, then queue spawn
task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc123 --role developer --background --agent claude --model claude-opus-4-6 --budget 5.0  # explicit claude + model
task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc123 --role developer --background --agent codex --model gpt-5.5 --reasoning-effort xhigh        # recommended codex path for code and analysis
task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc123 --role developer --background --agent codex --model gpt-5.3-codex --reasoning-effort xhigh  # explicit code-specialized override
task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc123 --role developer --background --agent codex --model gpt-5.3-codex-spark --reasoning-effort xhigh  # codex fast path on spark
task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc123 --role researcher --background --agent codex --model gpt-5.5 --reasoning-effort xhigh  # recommended codex path for thinking / architecture
task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc123 --role developer --background                    # board-centric: README + checklist + precondition resources
task-board spawn status RUN-260320-abc123                                            # inspect tracked run state
task-board spawn wait RUN-260320-abc123                                              # block on tracked run state after RUN exists
task-board spawn events RUN-260320-abc123                                            # replay durable run events (supports --cursor/--follow)
task-board spawn watch RUN-260320-abc123                                             # follow durable run-event notifications

# Auth (always local, never sent to server)
task-board login sampleuser tb_4lc6...                                        # store token in Keychain and select active user outside repo config
task-board login admin tb_UJTW... --remote https://board.example.com          # explicit remote bootstrap
task-board logout                                                              # remove selected user's token
task-board whoami                                                              # show remote URL + active user + token status
task-board switch-user admin                                                   # switch active user without touching versioned config
task-board q 'whoami()'                                                        # whoami via query DSL
task-board q 'project_config()'                                                # mode + board source + effective remote context
task-board m 'login(user=sampleuser, token=tb_xxx)'                           # login via mutation DSL
task-board m 'switch_user(user=admin)'                                         # switch via mutation DSL

# CLI utilities
task-board grep "AudioRecorder"                            # full-text search across board files (local only)
task-board validate                                        # check board structure (local only)
task-board plan EPIC-260218-abc123 --render --format png   # render hierarchy graph locally from the plan model
task-board plan --render --layout phases                   # render phases graph locally from the plan model
task-board tui                                             # interactive terminal dashboard
```

---

## Task Board Structure

### Hierarchy

```
Epic → Story → Task/Bug
```

- **Epic** = large feature / module
- **Story** = specific functionality within epic
- **Task** = atomic unit of work
- **Bug** = defect tracked within a story

### Naming Convention

**Distributed IDs** — each element gets a unique ID based on date + random hash.

```
EPIC-260203-a1b2c3_recording/
  STORY-260203-d4e5f6_audio-capture/
    TASK-260203-g7h8i9_audiorecorder-interface/
    TASK-260203-j0k1l2_implementation/
    BUG-260203-m3n4o5_some-bug/
```

Format: `{TYPE}-{YYMMDD}-{hash}_{kebab-case-name}`
- `EPIC-YYMMDD-xxxxxx_name`
- `STORY-YYMMDD-xxxxxx_name`
- `TASK-YYMMDD-xxxxxx_name`
- `BUG-YYMMDD-xxxxxx_name`

Where:
- `YYMMDD` — creation date (year, month, day)
- `xxxxxx` — 6-character base36 hash (collision-resistant)

IDs are globally unique and work in parallel environments (no counter conflicts).

### Directory Layout

```
.task-board/
├── .resources/                   # Flat resource storage (managed by CLI)
│   ├── TASK-260203-g7h8i9/       # Resources keyed by element ID
│   │   ├── design.md             # Precondition: input for the task
│   │   └── results.md            # Outcome: work product
│   └── STORY-260203-d4e5f6/
│       └── research.md
├── EPIC-260203-a1b2c3_recording/
│   ├── README.md                 # Epic description, scope, AC
│   ├── progress.md               # Status, blockedBy, checklist, notes, resource refs
│   ├── STORY-260203-d4e5f6_audio-capture/
│   │   ├── README.md
│   │   ├── progress.md
│   │   ├── TASK-260203-g7h8i9_interface/
│   │   │   ├── README.md
│   │   │   └── progress.md
│   │   ├── TASK-260203-j0k1l2_implementation/
│   │   │   ├── README.md

 succeeded in 0ms:
│   │   │   └── progress.md
│   │   └── BUG-260203-m3n4o5_crash-on-start/
│   │       ├── README.md
│   │       └── progress.md
│   └── STORY-260203-p6q7r8_amplitude/
│       └── ...
└── EPIC-260203-s9t0u1_storage/
    └── ...
```

No `system.md` needed — IDs are self-contained and don't require global counters.

---

## Statuses

9 statuses: `backlog` → `analysis` → `to-dev` → `development` → `to-review` → `reviewing` → `done`. Plus `closed` and `blocked`.

For full status flow, auto-promotion/reopen, blocked vs is_blocked — see [`references/statuses.md`](references/statuses.md).

---

## File Formats

Each element directory contains two files:
- **README.md** — static description (what the element is, scope, acceptance criteria). Does not change during execution.
- **progress.md** — dynamic lifecycle journal (status, assignment, timestamps, dependencies, checklist, notes). Updated throughout execution.

Dependencies are bidirectional and auto-escalate across parent boundaries.

For detailed format specifications, field descriptions, and examples, see [`references/file-formats.md`](references/file-formats.md).

---

## Resources & Bugs

Resources are linked to board elements via DSL mutations. Two types:
- **Precondition** — inputs for the task (instructions, specs, design docs). Used by `task-board spawn` to compose agent prompts.
- **Outcome** — work products (research results, implementation notes). Persisted for other agents/tasks to consume.

```bash
# Create resource
task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc123, name=TASK-260218-abc123_design.md, content="...", type=precondition, description="Architecture design")'
task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc123, name=TASK-260218-abc123_results.md, content="...", type=outcome, description="Research findings")'

# Replace existing resource
task-board m 'update_resource(TASK-260218-abc123, name=TASK-260218-abc123_results.md, content="revised findings", type=outcome, description="Research findings v2")'

# Delete resource
task-board m --confirm 'delete_resource(TASK-260218-abc123, name=TASK-260218-abc123_design.md)'
```

Resources are stored flat in `.task-board/.resources/<elementID>/` and referenced from `progress.md`. Bugs live inside stories alongside tasks.

For resource workflow and bug tracking — see [`references/resources-and-bugs.md`](references/resources-and-bugs.md).

---

## Workflow

### Full Development Cycle (MANDATORY)

When the user asks to build/implement something, the agent MUST follow this end-to-end flow:

#### Spec
- Specs live in the `.spec/` directory (one or more `.md` files), not in a single `SPEC.md`
- Create `.spec/` if it doesn't exist; add focused spec files per topic/feature (e.g. `.spec/auth.md`, `.spec/api.md`)
- Clarify requirements with the user if anything is ambiguous
- `.spec/` is the source of truth — all work traces back to it

#### Plan on the Board
- Create epics and stories: `task-board m 'create(type=epic, name=..., description="...")'`
- Refine each element: query with `task-board q 'get(ID) { full }'`, clarify gaps, update via `task-board m 'set_details(ID, description="...")'`
- No element should have placeholder text — description and AC must be complete and unambiguous

#### Story Detailing, Phase Planning, Execution (MANDATORY)

Full planning and execution workflow — story detailing, phase planning, user approval, pre-launch checklist, sub-agent execution, supervision, visualization — see [`references/planning-workflow.md`](references/planning-workflow.md).

Key points:
- **Story detailing before planning** — all stories must have tasks before phase planning
- **Use `task-board q 'plan(...)'` as the canonical planning API** — it returns the planning model (scope, phases, critical path). Use `task-board plan` only as a local pretty-print / render / save facade over that same model. NEVER build phases manually or write plan files by hand
- **Dump plan to `.planning/`** — after planning, save to `.planning/{YYMMDD}_{HHmmss}_{topic}.md` for session recovery. Use `task-board plan --save`
- **User approval MANDATORY** — never start execution without user confirmation
- **Pre-launch checklist** — model, status, assignment, concrete IDs, first command
- **Coordinator is SUPERVISOR** — never writes code, only delegates to sub-agents

#### Research / Analysis Tasks

Research workflow, resource linking, document structure, status flow — see [`references/research-workflow.md`](references/research-workflow.md).

Key points:
- Research results are linked to board elements via `task-board m 'add_resource(..., type=outcome)'` on first write and `update_resource(...)` on revisions
- Broadly useful research also persists in **`.research/`** directory (project-level)
- Status flow: `backlog → analysis → to-review → reviewing → done` (skip `development`; coordinator spawns `task-board spawn TASK-... --role reviewer --background` after `to-review`)
- Always link research output as an outcome resource on the task, and include the task ID in the resource name

### Iterative Refinement (for individual elements)

When creating ANY element (epic/story/task/bug), the agent MUST:

1. **Create** element via `task-board m 'create(type=..., name=..., description="...")'`
2. **Read** the element: `task-board q 'get(ID) { full }'`
3. **Clarify** — if description is vague or has gaps, ask the user
4. **Update** via `task-board m 'set_details(ID, description="...", ac="...")'`
5. **Repeat** steps 2-4 until description is exhaustive
6. Element is **ready** only when description and AC are complete and unambiguous

### Project Start

- Create elements: `task-board m 'create(type=epic, name=auth-system, description="...")'`
- Create stories: `task-board m 'create(type=story, parent=EPIC-260218-abc, name=login)'`
- Detail tasks: `task-board m 'create(type=task, parent=STORY-260218-abc, name=impl)'`
- Set dependencies: `task-board m 'link(STORY-260218-def, blocked_by=STORY-260218-abc)'`
- **Generate phases**: `task-board q 'plan(EPIC-260218-abc, mode=children)'` — only after all stories have tasks and dependencies are set

### Spawning Agents for Tasks

The **coordinator never writes code** — it delegates to tracked background child runs via `task-board spawn ... --background`.

Treat [`references/tracked-background-spawn.md`](references/tracked-background-spawn.md) as the canonical operator-facing spawn contract. The guidance below is the workflow summary agents should follow.

**`--role` is REQUIRED.** Every spawn must specify a role. Choose the role based on the task:

| Task type | Role |
|-----------|------|
| Research, analysis, investigation | `--role researcher` |
| Code implementation, bugfixes | `--role developer` |
| Writing tests | `--role tester` |
| Story decomposition, architecture | `--role solution-architect` |
| Documentation | `--role doc-writer` |
| Code review, quality check | `--role reviewer` |

**Workflow:**

1. **Preflight runtime** — run `task-board q 'project_config()'` before spawning so you know whether this cwd is using a local board or a remote profile
2. **Prepare task** — ensure element has clear title, description, scope, AC
3. **Add task-specific DoD on the board** — checklist items on the element are the task-specific DoD that spawn validates before launch
   ```bash
   task-board m 'add_checklist_item(TASK-260218-abc, text="Handle edge case X")'
   task-board m 'add_checklist_item(TASK-260218-abc, text="Preserve existing API response shape")'
   ```
4. **Link instruction** (optional) — add precondition resource:
   ```bash
   # Inline text instruction
   task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc, name=TASK-260218-abc_impl-guide.md, content="...", type=precondition, description="Implementation guide")'

   # File or URL attachment
   task-board resource add TASK-260218-abc ./TASK-260218-abc_impl-guide.md --type precondition

   # Chat attachment only (no local path yet) — requires alexis-agents-infra:
   # https://github.com/relux-works/alexis-agents-infra
   agents-attachments materialize
   task-board resource add TASK-260218-abc "$(agents-attachments path attachment-001)" --name TASK-260218-abc_attachment-001.bin --type precondition
   ```
5. **Spawn with role in background** — `task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc --role developer --background` (auto-composes prompt from role + README + checklist DoD + precondition resources)
   - With instruction validation: `task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc --role developer --background --instruction TASK-260218-abc_impl-guide.md`
   - Reviews are spawned too: `task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc --role reviewer --background`
6. **Capture the run id** — tracked background spawn returns `RUN-...`; use it as the coordinator handle for that child execution
   - CLI output now prints non-blocking monitor commands with a seeded cursor (`RUN-ID:0`) and preserves the active `task-board` executable / board context
   - JSON output exposes the same self-contained contract under `observation` (`cursor`, `eventsCommand`, `watchCommand`, `waitCommand`, `inSessionDelivery`)
7. **Monitor** — `task-board spawn status RUN-...`, `task-board spawn events RUN-... --cursor ...`, `task-board spawn watch RUN-...`, `task-board spawn wait RUN-...`, and `task-board q --format compact 'agents()'`
   - Directive plane: `task-board spawn directives RUN-...` to inspect durable operator directives and `task-board spawn directive RUN-... <kind>` to request `cancel`, `pause_after_checkpoint`, `restart`, `reroute_after_checkpoint`, `request_progress`, or `nudge`
8. **Review via child run** — when an implementer/tester/researcher sets `to-review`, treat that as "ready for review", not done. Spawn a review child with `--role reviewer --background`; the parent coordinates the review result and only then marks `done` or sends back to `to-dev`

Spawn is task-centric:
- Primary inputs are task ID + role
- `task-board q 'project_config()'` is the supported preflight check before spawning or auditing
- Agent selection follows the current runtime (Claude sessions -> `claude`, Codex sessions -> `codex`) and can be overridden with `--agent`
- Model selection is optional
- Task description comes from the board README
- Task-specific DoD comes from the board checklist
- Role baseline DoD is appended after task-specific DoD
- Precondition resources carry additional instructions, screenshots, specs, and artifacts
- Hidden legacy `--task-path` and `--dod-path` flags are compatibility-only appenders; they do not replace the board README/checklist workflow and should not be part of the normal contract
- Spawn returns a tracked `RUN-...` handle; use `task-board spawn wait RUN-...` only after a run exists and the parent needs an explicit synchronization barrier
- Spawn output includes coordinator observation hints for non-blocking monitoring (`watch`, `events --cursor RUN-ID:0`, `wait`) and keeps them runnable in the same executable / board context that produced the run
- `task-board spawn --json` exposes the same contract in `observation.*`; `observation.inSessionDelivery=true` only when the current Codex orchestrator session was launched through `task-board codex`
- Spawn run events use replay cursor tokens (`RUN-ID:seq`) so local CLI, TUI, and remote watchers can resume from the same durable position
- Spawn directives are first-class durable records with acknowledgement state; use `spawn directive` / `spawn directives` instead of ad hoc notes for cancel/pause/restart/reroute intent
- Watcher notifications are external observation surfaces by default; `task-board codex` adds runtime-native terminal delivery back into the active Codex thread
- Soft directives are cooperative checkpoint signals only. Spawned agents can inspect them through `TASK_BOARD_RUN_ID` + `task-board spawn directives "$TASK_BOARD_RUN_ID"`; do not assume live in-session push
- Coordinators must not wrap `task-board spawn` in `&`, `nohup`, or runtime background wrappers; `--background` already returns a tracked run
- Spawn validates that the board task brief is usable: description and acceptance criteria must be real, not placeholders or one-line fluff
- Repeated spawn on the same task must be idempotent: existing injected checklist items are not duplicated
- When auditing spawn docs/help/source, exclude `.temp/**` from repo-wide searches so stale task-scoped worktrees do not look like current contract files

### Model Selection Guide

**Always use top-tier models.** A bug from a weaker model on a simple task will cost you 10x more to debug on a complex one.

| Task type | Agent | Model | --reasoning-effort | Notes |
|-----------|-------|-------|--------------------|-------|
| Code implementation | codex | gpt-5.5 (default) | **xhigh** | Codex spawn enables live web search by default; do not use `minimal` |
| Code implementation (override) | codex | gpt-5.3-codex | **xhigh** | Use explicitly when you want the coding-specialized variant |
| Fast code iteration | codex | gpt-5.3-codex-spark | **xhigh** | Valid tracked background spawn option when speed matters more than depth |
| Thinking/architecture | codex | **gpt-5.5 (default)** | **xhigh** | Use the same top-tier default here too |
| All tasks | claude | claude-opus-4-6 (default) | - | Always opus. No exceptions |

Other models may be available, but the recommended board workflow is still to use the strongest model for the chosen agent.

**Budget: unlimited by default.** Don't pass `--budget` unless the user explicitly asks to cap spending. Let agents finish their work — a $5 cap on a $3 task means a failed half-done agent + a retry that costs $6 total. Unlimited is cheaper than retries.

The CLI validates model choices and warns (never blocks) when:
- Model is unknown (forward-compatible — new models pass through)
- Model belongs to a different agent type
- Model benefits from `--reasoning-effort` but none is set
- `--reasoning-effort` is set on a model that doesn't support it

### Working on a Task (as sub-agent)

1. Assign + start → `task-board m 'assign(TASK-260218-abc, agent=agent-name); set_status(TASK-260218-abc, status=development)'`
2. Work until the task is genuinely complete or objectively blocked. Do not stop with the task parked in `analysis`, `development`, `testing`, or `reviewing` just because one local action finished.
3. Stop and escalate if completion would require a forced fit: document the constraint, failed assumption, viable options, and exact human/product/architecture decision needed. Do not pile on compensating tests, stubs, flags, or priority rules to make an invalid model appear to work.
4. Update checklist → `task-board m 'check_item(TASK-260218-abc, item=1)'`
5. Save results → `task-board m 'add_resource(TASK-260218-abc, name=TASK-260218-abc_results.md, content="...", type=outcome, description="Implementation notes")'`
6. Ready for review → `task-board m 'set_status(TASK-260218-abc, status=to-review)'`
7. Or blocked → `task-board m 'set_status(TASK-260218-abc, status=blocked); set_notes(TASK-260218-abc, text="Blocked: concrete blocker and evidence")'`
8. Orchestrator confirms producer evidence, spawns a tracked reviewer child (`task-board spawn TASK-260218-abc --role reviewer --background`), waits or monitors the returned `RUN-...`, then routes by the reviewer-child verdict: accepted → `done`, changes requested → `to-dev`

Human-facing language is part of the contract: a producer ending at `to-review` says "ready for review" or "handed off to review", not "done"/"complete"/"finished"/"final"/"готово". Only a reviewer/coordinator may call the board task done, and only after the board status is actually `done`.

### Dependencies

```bash
# TASK-B depends on TASK-A
task-board m 'link(TASK-260218-def, blocked_by=TASK-260218-abc)'

# CLI will refuse to move TASK-B to development while TASK-A is not done
task-board m 'set_status(TASK-260218-def, status=development)'
# Error: cannot start TASK-260218-def — blocked by: TASK-260218-abc

# Remove dependency
task-board m 'unlink(TASK-260218-def, blocked_by=TASK-260218-abc)'
```

### Board Review

```bash
# Queries (use --format compact for token efficiency)
task-board q 'schema()'                                                          # discover fields, presets, operations
task-board q 'project_config()'                                                  # confirm this repo is local or remote before agent work
task-board q --format compact 'summary()'                                        # quick overview
task-board q --format compact 'get(TASK-260218-abc) { full }'                    # full element details
task-board q --format compact 'list(type=task, status=development) { overview }'  # what's in progress
task-board q --format compact 'list(type=task, blocked=true) { id name status }'  # what's blocked
task-board q --format compact 'agents()'                                         # agent dashboard
task-board q --format compact 'plan(EPIC-260218-abc, mode=children)'             # execution phases

# Full-text search (local only)
task-board grep "AudioRecorder"

# Validation (local only)
task-board validate
```

